The paper investigates network creation games from a game-theoretic point of view, which suggests that it could belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The models proposed are inspired by social networks, which could also place it in the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper analyzes various properties of the sequential versions of the model, which could suggest it belongs to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also discusses the complexity of computing a best response, which could place it in the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the Price of Anarchy, which could suggest it belongs to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category.
